back even before and say, OK,

00:34:22.436 --> 00:34:23.969 align:middle line:90%
what can we learn from this?

00:34:23.969 --> 00:34:25.807 align:middle line:84%
Was there a reason for
this or blah, blah,

00:34:25.807 --> 00:34:29.810 align:middle line:84%
blah to go get some
learnings about the mission.

00:34:29.810 --> 00:34:32.139 align:middle line:84%
So that's where I was
like, oh interesting.

00:34:32.139 --> 00:34:34.100 align:middle line:84%
And then I learned
Michael Newton's work.

00:34:34.100 --> 00:34:34.600 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:34:34.600 --> 00:34:38.429 align:middle line:84%
So I started to, basically,
train with all the big guys

00:34:38.429 --> 00:34:41.060 align:middle line:84%
whether it's the Newton
Institute, Brian Wise, Dolores

00:34:41.060 --> 00:34:44.340 align:middle line:84%
Cannon, and went to Tom
Silver at some point.

00:34:44.340 --> 00:34:49.320 align:middle line:84%
And I just went to study all
the golden nuggets, basically,

00:34:49.320 --> 00:34:53.320 align:middle line:84%
and just created my own approach
and started teaching people

00:34:53.320 --> 00:34:54.642 align:middle line:90%
about it.

00:34:54.642 --> 00:34:56.100 align:middle line:84%
>>LILOU: What's
still, to this day,

00:34:56.100 --> 00:34:59.850 align:middle line:84%
the most surprising thing
about this whole adventure?

00:34:59.850 --> 00:35:02.590 align:middle line:84%
>>CHABOT: The most
surprising thing?

00:35:02.590 --> 00:35:03.665 align:middle line:90%
I mean, each time--

00:35:03.665 --> 00:35:04.815 align:middle line:84%
>>LILOU: That you're
still like, just, wow.

00:35:04.815 --> 00:35:07.180 align:middle line:84%
>>CHABOT: I mean, just
yesterday, Lilou, you know,

00:35:07.180 --> 00:35:12.290 align:middle line:84%
when you have a client
which connects with a guide

00:35:12.290 --> 00:35:14.870 align:middle line:84%
